WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.610 --> 00:00:03.140
MALE SPEAKER:
Welcome, everybody.

00:00:03.140 --> 00:00:07.620
Six days ago, astronaut
Mark Whatrey--

00:00:07.620 --> 00:00:08.370
ANDY WEIR: Watney.

00:00:08.370 --> 00:00:10.420
MALE SPEAKER: --became
one of the first men

00:00:10.420 --> 00:00:12.920
to walk on the surface of Mars.

00:00:12.920 --> 00:00:16.390
Now he may be the
first man to die there.

00:00:16.390 --> 00:00:18.870
Will he?

00:00:18.870 --> 00:00:22.040
Andy Weir's brilliant
debut novel, "The Martian,"

00:00:22.040 --> 00:00:26.920
is a gripping story of
survival against all odds.

00:00:26.920 --> 00:00:29.480
The astronaut is stranded
millions of miles

00:00:29.480 --> 00:00:32.310
from the nearest human
being with no way

00:00:32.310 --> 00:00:35.450
to even signal Earth
that he is alive.

00:00:35.450 --> 00:00:37.450
And even if you he
could get word out,

00:00:37.450 --> 00:00:40.600
his food would be gone years
before a rescue mission could

00:00:40.600 --> 00:00:43.230
arrive.

00:00:43.230 --> 00:00:46.940
Andy Weir, he's our neighbor
here in Mountain View,

00:00:46.940 --> 00:00:48.450
a longtime programmer.

00:00:48.450 --> 00:00:53.880
He got his first job at 15 years
of age at Sandia National Labs.

00:00:53.880 --> 00:00:58.030
He wrote code for Warcraft II.

00:00:58.030 --> 00:01:01.010
And he's now working
at MobileIron,

00:01:01.010 --> 00:01:04.129
where he's working
on Android codes.

00:01:04.129 --> 00:01:08.250
And actually, we talked a little
bit how he likes the platform,

00:01:08.250 --> 00:01:12.110
and he didn't have
too many complaints.

00:01:12.110 --> 00:01:16.370
I guess this is kudos to you
guys from the Android group.

00:01:16.370 --> 00:01:23.080
I am pleased to present
the book, "The Martian."

00:01:23.080 --> 00:01:25.920
Andy will be talking
to us today about it

00:01:25.920 --> 00:01:29.140
and showing some of the
technical details that

00:01:29.140 --> 00:01:30.460
went into the book.

00:01:30.460 --> 00:01:31.960
And please give a warm welcome.

00:01:31.960 --> 00:01:38.390
[APPLAUSE]

00:01:38.390 --> 00:01:40.487
ANDY WEIR: So, like he
said, I'm Andy Weir.

00:01:40.487 --> 00:01:41.570
And I wrote "The Martian."

00:01:41.570 --> 00:01:45.177
I'm going to be talking
to you about that today.

00:01:45.177 --> 00:01:47.260
When they told me that I'd
be doing a Google Talk,

00:01:47.260 --> 00:01:48.910
they said, you're
going to want to make

00:01:48.910 --> 00:01:50.820
about 40 minutes of content.

00:01:50.820 --> 00:01:53.910
I don't think I'm going to
make 40 minutes of content.

00:01:53.910 --> 00:01:56.850
But I'll just say what I have
to say until I'm out of stuff

00:01:56.850 --> 00:02:00.570
to say, and then
I'll take questions.

00:02:00.570 --> 00:02:02.500
So you just got the
summary of the book.

00:02:02.500 --> 00:02:03.320
But I'm going to do a reading.

00:02:03.320 --> 00:02:04.490
I'm going to start us
off with a reading.

00:02:04.490 --> 00:02:05.820
And then I'm going to
start talking about some

00:02:05.820 --> 00:02:08.520
of the technical stuff that
went into making the book.

00:02:08.520 --> 00:02:11.000
The reading's going to
be about 10 minutes.

00:02:11.000 --> 00:02:14.410
And it's just the first chapter.

00:02:14.410 --> 00:02:17.620
So it's about four
or five pages.

00:02:17.620 --> 00:02:20.035
Also, the reading will
include profanities.

00:02:20.035 --> 00:02:21.670
I hope nobody's
bothered by that.

00:02:21.670 --> 00:02:23.560
I don't see any
children out there.

00:02:23.560 --> 00:02:27.630
So I'm just going
to jump right in.

00:02:27.630 --> 00:02:29.680
Log entry, Sol 6.

00:02:29.680 --> 00:02:31.150
I'm pretty much fucked.

00:02:31.150 --> 00:02:32.570
That's my considered opinion.

00:02:32.570 --> 00:02:33.094
Fucked.

00:02:33.094 --> 00:02:35.760
Six days into what should be the
greatest two months of my life,

00:02:35.760 --> 00:02:37.380
and it's turned
into a nightmare.

00:02:37.380 --> 00:02:38.530
I don't even know
who'll read this.

00:02:38.530 --> 00:02:40.196
I guess someone will
find it eventually,

00:02:40.196 --> 00:02:41.420
maybe 100 years from now.

00:02:41.420 --> 00:02:43.506
For the record, I
didn't die on Sol 6.

00:02:43.506 --> 00:02:45.380
Certainly the rest of
the crew thought I did.

00:02:45.380 --> 00:02:46.374
And I can't blame them.

00:02:46.374 --> 00:02:48.540
Maybe there'll be a day of
national mourning for me.

00:02:48.540 --> 00:02:50.290
And my Wikipedia page
will say Mark Watney

00:02:50.290 --> 00:02:52.650
is the only human being
to have died on Mars.

00:02:52.650 --> 00:02:53.870
And it'll be right, probably.

00:02:53.870 --> 00:02:55.170
Because I'll surely die here.

00:02:55.170 --> 00:02:57.780
Just not on Sol 6 when
everyone thinks I did.

00:02:57.780 --> 00:02:58.330
Let's see.

00:02:58.330 --> 00:02:59.570
Where do I begin?

00:02:59.570 --> 00:03:02.037
The Ares program-- mankind
reaching out to Mars

00:03:02.037 --> 00:03:04.370
to send people to another
planet for the very first time

00:03:04.370 --> 00:03:06.972
and expand the horizons of
humanity, blah, blah, blah.

00:03:06.972 --> 00:03:09.180
The Ares 1 crew did their
thing and came back heroes.

00:03:09.180 --> 00:03:11.580
They got the parades and
fame and love of the world.

00:03:11.580 --> 00:03:13.999
Ares 2 did the same thing in
a different location on Mars.

00:03:13.999 --> 00:03:16.040
They got a firm handshake
and a hot cup of coffee

00:03:16.040 --> 00:03:17.300
when they got home.

00:03:17.300 --> 00:03:18.030
Ares 3?

00:03:18.030 --> 00:03:19.230
Well, that's my mission.

00:03:19.230 --> 00:03:20.370
Well, not mine, per se.

00:03:20.370 --> 00:03:21.620
Commander Lewis was in charge.

00:03:21.620 --> 00:03:23.160
I was just one of her crew.

00:03:23.160 --> 00:03:25.642
Actually, I was the very lowest
ranked member of the crew.

00:03:25.642 --> 00:03:27.350
I would only be in
command of the mission

00:03:27.350 --> 00:03:28.860
if I were the only
remaining person.

00:03:28.860 --> 00:03:29.776
Hey, what do you know?

00:03:29.776 --> 00:03:31.400
I'm in command.

00:03:31.400 --> 00:03:32.900
I wonder if this
log'll be recovered

00:03:32.900 --> 00:03:34.749
before the rest of the
crew die of old age.

00:03:34.749 --> 00:03:36.540
I presume they got back
to Earth all right.

00:03:36.540 --> 00:03:38.460
Guys, if you're reading
this, it wasn't your fault.

00:03:38.460 --> 00:03:39.660
You did what you had to do.

00:03:39.660 --> 00:03:41.630
In your position, I would
have done the same thing.

00:03:41.630 --> 00:03:42.340
I don't blame you.

00:03:42.340 --> 00:03:43.423
And I'm glad you survived.

00:03:45.782 --> 00:03:47.740
I guess I should explain
how Mars missions work

00:03:47.740 --> 00:03:49.580
for any laymen who
may be reading this.

00:03:49.580 --> 00:03:52.121
We got to Earth orbit the normal
way through an ordinary ship

00:03:52.121 --> 00:03:52.914
to "Hermes."

00:03:52.914 --> 00:03:54.330
All the Ares
missions use "Hermes"

00:03:54.330 --> 00:03:55.480
to get to and from Mars.

00:03:55.480 --> 00:03:58.754
It's really big and it cost a
lot, so NASA only built one.

00:03:58.754 --> 00:04:01.170
Once we got to "Hermes," four
additional unmanned missions

00:04:01.170 --> 00:04:03.520
brought us fuel and supplies
while we prepared for our trip.

00:04:03.520 --> 00:04:05.520
Once everything was a
"go," we set out for Mars,

00:04:05.520 --> 00:04:06.594
but not very fast.

00:04:06.594 --> 00:04:08.260
Gone are the days of
heavy chemical fuel

00:04:08.260 --> 00:04:10.320
burns and trans-Mars
injection orbits.

00:04:10.320 --> 00:04:11.792
"Hermes" is powered
by ion engines.

00:04:11.792 --> 00:04:13.500
They throw argon out
the back of the ship

00:04:13.500 --> 00:04:15.930
really fast to get a tiny
amount of acceleration.

00:04:15.930 --> 00:04:18.079
The thing is it doesn't
take much reactant mass.

00:04:18.079 --> 00:04:20.940
So a little argon and a
nuclear reactor to power things

00:04:20.940 --> 00:04:23.261
let us accelerate constantly
the whole way there.

00:04:23.261 --> 00:04:24.760
You'd be amazed how
fast you can get

00:04:24.760 --> 00:04:27.762
going with a tiny
acceleration over a long time.

00:04:27.762 --> 00:04:29.970
I could regale you with
tales of how we had great fun

00:04:29.970 --> 00:04:31.132
on the trip, but I won't.

00:04:31.132 --> 00:04:32.840
I don't feel like
re-living it right now.

00:04:32.840 --> 00:04:35.080
Suffice it to say we
got to Mars 124 days

00:04:35.080 --> 00:04:36.970
later without
strangling each other.

00:04:36.970 --> 00:04:39.560
From there we took the
MDV, Mars Descent Vehicle,

00:04:39.560 --> 00:04:40.560
to the surface.

00:04:40.560 --> 00:04:42.980
The MDV is basically a big
can with some light thrusters

00:04:42.980 --> 00:04:44.100
and parachutes attached.

00:04:44.100 --> 00:04:46.320
Its sole purpose is to get
six humans from Mars orbit

00:04:46.320 --> 00:04:48.199
to the surface without
killing any of them.

00:04:48.199 --> 00:04:50.490
And now we come to the real
trick of Mars exploration--

00:04:50.490 --> 00:04:52.370
having all your shit
there in advance.

00:04:52.370 --> 00:04:54.850
A total of 14 unmanned
missions deposited everything

00:04:54.850 --> 00:04:56.392
we would need for
surface operations.

00:04:56.392 --> 00:04:58.183
They tried their best
to land on the supply

00:04:58.183 --> 00:05:00.819
vessels in the same general area
and did a reasonably good job.

00:05:00.819 --> 00:05:02.610
Supplies aren't nearly
so fragile as humans

00:05:02.610 --> 00:05:04.170
and can hit the
ground really hard,

00:05:04.170 --> 00:05:05.829
but they tend to
bounce around a lot.

00:05:05.829 --> 00:05:07.370
Naturally they didn't
send us to Mars

00:05:07.370 --> 00:05:09.160
until they confirmed that
all the supplies had made it

00:05:09.160 --> 00:05:11.368
to the surface and their
containers weren't breached.

00:05:11.368 --> 00:05:13.330
Start to finish,
including supply missions,

00:05:13.330 --> 00:05:15.520
a Mars mission takes
about three years.

00:05:15.520 --> 00:05:17.890
In fact, there were Ares 3
supplies en route to Mars

00:05:17.890 --> 00:05:20.441
while the Ares 2 crew
were on their way home.

00:05:20.441 --> 00:05:22.940
The most important piece of the
advance supplies, of course,

00:05:22.940 --> 00:05:25.314
was the MAV, the
Mars Ascent Vehicle.

00:05:25.314 --> 00:05:26.980
That's how we would
get back to "Hermes"

00:05:26.980 --> 00:05:28.720
after surface operations
were complete.

00:05:28.720 --> 00:05:31.070
The MAV was soft landed
as opposed to the balloon

00:05:31.070 --> 00:05:32.705
bounce fest the
other supplies had.

00:05:32.705 --> 00:05:35.080
Of course, it was in constant
communication with Houston,

00:05:35.080 --> 00:05:36.910
and if there had been
any problems with it,

00:05:36.910 --> 00:05:39.770
we would have passed by Mars and
gone home without ever landing.

00:05:39.770 --> 00:05:41.070
The MAV is pretty cool.

00:05:41.070 --> 00:05:42.930
It turns out through a neat
set of chemical reactions

00:05:42.930 --> 00:05:45.388
with the Martian atmosphere,
for every kilogram of hydrogen

00:05:45.388 --> 00:05:48.074
you bring to Mars, you can
make 13 kilograms of fuel.

00:05:48.074 --> 00:05:49.240
It's a slow process, though.

00:05:49.240 --> 00:05:51.050
It takes 24 months
to fill the tank.

00:05:51.050 --> 00:05:53.290
That's why they sent it
long before we got there.

00:05:53.290 --> 00:05:54.706
You can imagine
how disappointed I

00:05:54.706 --> 00:05:57.352
was when I discovered
the MAV was gone.

00:05:57.352 --> 00:05:59.560
It was a ridiculous sequence
of events that led to me

00:05:59.560 --> 00:06:01.851
almost dying, and an even
more ridiculous sequence that

00:06:01.851 --> 00:06:02.770
led to me surviving.

00:06:02.770 --> 00:06:04.144
The mission is
designed to handle

00:06:04.144 --> 00:06:06.539
sandstorm gusts
of up to 150 KPH.

00:06:06.539 --> 00:06:08.080
So Houston got
understandably nervous

00:06:08.080 --> 00:06:10.670
when we got whacked
with 175 KPH winds.

00:06:10.670 --> 00:06:12.420
We all got in our
flight suits and huddled

00:06:12.420 --> 00:06:14.711
in the middle of the Hab just
in case it lost pressure.

00:06:14.711 --> 00:06:16.180
But they Hab wasn't the problem.

00:06:16.180 --> 00:06:17.289
The MAV is a spaceship.

00:06:17.289 --> 00:06:18.580
It has a lot of delicate parts.

00:06:18.580 --> 00:06:20.496
It can put up with storms
to a certain extent,

00:06:20.496 --> 00:06:22.340
but it can't just get
sand blasted forever.

00:06:22.340 --> 00:06:24.131
After an hour and a
half of sustained wind,

00:06:24.131 --> 00:06:25.340
NASA gave the order to abort.

00:06:25.340 --> 00:06:27.547
Nobody wanted to stop a
month-long mission after only

00:06:27.547 --> 00:06:29.680
six days, but if the MAV
took any more punishment,

00:06:29.680 --> 00:06:32.350
we'd have all gotten
stranded down there.

00:06:32.350 --> 00:06:34.960
We had to go out in the storm
to get from the Hab to the MAV.

00:06:34.960 --> 00:06:36.251
And that was going to be risky.

00:06:36.251 --> 00:06:37.590
But what choice did we have?

00:06:37.590 --> 00:06:39.290
Everyone made it but me.

00:06:39.290 --> 00:06:41.520
Our main communications
dish, which relayed signals

00:06:41.520 --> 00:06:43.680
from the Hab to "Hermes,"
acted like a parachute getting

00:06:43.680 --> 00:06:45.940
torn from its foundation and
carried with the torrent.

00:06:45.940 --> 00:06:47.770
Along the way, it crashed
through the reception antenna

00:06:47.770 --> 00:06:48.299
array.

00:06:48.299 --> 00:06:49.840
Then one of those
long, thin antennae

00:06:49.840 --> 00:06:51.270
slammed into me end first.

00:06:51.270 --> 00:06:53.540
It tore through my suit like
a bullet through butter.

00:06:53.540 --> 00:06:56.494
And I felt the worst pain in my
life as it ripped open my side.

00:06:56.494 --> 00:06:58.410
I vaguely remember having
the wind knocked out

00:06:58.410 --> 00:06:59.910
of me-- pulled out
of me, really--

00:06:59.910 --> 00:07:01.785
and my ears popping
painfully is the pressure

00:07:01.785 --> 00:07:02.630
in my suit escaped.

00:07:02.630 --> 00:07:04.546
The last thing I remember
was seeing Johanssen

00:07:04.546 --> 00:07:06.680
hopelessly reaching
out toward me.

00:07:06.680 --> 00:07:08.520
I awoke to an oxygen
alarm in my suit,

00:07:08.520 --> 00:07:10.270
a steady obnoxious
beeping that aroused me

00:07:10.270 --> 00:07:14.660
from a deep and profound
desire to just fucking die.

00:07:14.660 --> 00:07:15.560
The storm had abated.

00:07:15.560 --> 00:07:17.800
I was face down, almost
totally buried in sand.

00:07:17.800 --> 00:07:19.210
As I groggily came
to, I wondered

00:07:19.210 --> 00:07:21.119
why I wasn't more dead.

00:07:21.119 --> 00:07:22.660
The antenna had
enough force to punch

00:07:22.660 --> 00:07:24.020
through the suit
and my side, but it

00:07:24.020 --> 00:07:25.310
had been stopped by my pelvis.

00:07:25.310 --> 00:07:26.976
So there was only one
hole in the suit--

00:07:26.976 --> 00:07:29.430
and a hole in me, of course.

00:07:29.430 --> 00:07:30.900
I'd been knocked
back quite a ways

00:07:30.900 --> 00:07:32.108
and rolled down a steep hill.

00:07:32.108 --> 00:07:33.490
Somehow I landed
face down, which

00:07:33.490 --> 00:07:35.620
forced the antenna into a
strongly oblique angle that

00:07:35.620 --> 00:07:37.453
put a lot of torque on
the hole in the suit.

00:07:37.453 --> 00:07:38.610
It made a weak seal.

00:07:38.610 --> 00:07:40.110
Then the copious
blood from my wound

00:07:40.110 --> 00:07:41.230
trickled down toward the hole.

00:07:41.230 --> 00:07:43.200
As the blood reached the site
of the breach, the water in it

00:07:43.200 --> 00:07:45.700
quickly evaporated from the
air flow and low pressure,

00:07:45.700 --> 00:07:47.374
leaving a gunky residue behind.

00:07:47.374 --> 00:07:49.790
More blood came in behind it
and was also reduced to gunk.

00:07:49.790 --> 00:07:51.450
Eventually it sealed
the gaps around the hole

00:07:51.450 --> 00:07:52.824
and reduced the
leak to something

00:07:52.824 --> 00:07:54.680
the suit could counteract.

00:07:54.680 --> 00:07:56.374
The suit did its job admirably.

00:07:56.374 --> 00:07:58.165
Sensing the drop in
pressure, it constantly

00:07:58.165 --> 00:08:00.584
flooded itself with air from
my nitrogen tank to equalize.

00:08:00.584 --> 00:08:02.250
Once the leak became
manageable, it only

00:08:02.250 --> 00:08:05.040
had to trickle new air in
slowly to relieve the air lost.

00:08:05.040 --> 00:08:07.989
After a while, the CO2, carbon
dioxide, absorbers in the suit

00:08:07.989 --> 00:08:10.280
were expended That's really
the limiting factor to life

00:08:10.280 --> 00:08:12.530
support-- not the amount of
oxygen you bring with you,

00:08:12.530 --> 00:08:14.340
but the amount of
CO2 you can remove.

00:08:14.340 --> 00:08:16.620
In the Hab, I have the
oxygenator, a large piece

00:08:16.620 --> 00:08:20.284
of equipment that breaks apart
CO2 to give the oxygen back.

00:08:20.284 --> 00:08:21.950
But the space suits
have to be portable.

00:08:21.950 --> 00:08:23.790
So they use a simple
chemical absorption

00:08:23.790 --> 00:08:25.580
process with expendable filters.

00:08:25.580 --> 00:08:28.304
I'd been asleep long enough
that my filters were useless.

00:08:28.304 --> 00:08:30.720
The suit saw this problem and
moved into an emergency mode

00:08:30.720 --> 00:08:32.309
the engineers call
"bloodletting."

00:08:32.309 --> 00:08:33.929
Having no way to
separate the CO2,

00:08:33.929 --> 00:08:36.470
the suit deliberately vented
air into the Martian atmosphere,

00:08:36.470 --> 00:08:37.940
then back-filled with nitrogen.

00:08:37.940 --> 00:08:39.340
Between the breach
and the bloodletting,

00:08:39.340 --> 00:08:40.659
it quickly ran out of nitrogen.

00:08:40.659 --> 00:08:42.846
All it had left
was my oxygen tank.

00:08:42.846 --> 00:08:44.970
So it did the only thing
it could to keep me alive.

00:08:44.970 --> 00:08:46.678
It started back-filling
with pure oxygen.

00:08:46.678 --> 00:08:49.084
I now risked dying
from oxygen toxicity

00:08:49.084 --> 00:08:50.750
as the excessively
high amount of oxygen

00:08:50.750 --> 00:08:53.250
threatened to burn up my nervous
system, lungs, and eyes--

00:08:53.250 --> 00:08:55.791
an ironic death for someone with
a leaky space suit, too much

00:08:55.791 --> 00:08:56.571
oxygen.

00:08:56.571 --> 00:08:59.070
Every step of the way would
have had beeping alarms, alerts,

00:08:59.070 --> 00:08:59.630
and warnings.

00:08:59.630 --> 00:09:02.055
But it was a high oxygen
morning that woke me.

00:09:02.055 --> 00:09:04.680
The sheer volume of training for
a space mission is astounding.

00:09:04.680 --> 00:09:07.200
I'd spent a week back on Earth
practicing emergency spacesuit

00:09:07.200 --> 00:09:07.700
drills.

00:09:07.700 --> 00:09:08.622
I knew what to do.

00:09:08.622 --> 00:09:10.330
Carefully reaching
the side of my helmet,

00:09:10.330 --> 00:09:11.220
I got the breach kit.

00:09:11.220 --> 00:09:13.490
It's nothing more than a funnel
with a valve at the small end

00:09:13.490 --> 00:09:15.780
and an unbelievably sticky
resin on the white end.

00:09:15.780 --> 00:09:18.284
The idea is you have
the valve open and stick

00:09:18.284 --> 00:09:19.450
the white end over the hole.

00:09:19.450 --> 00:09:20.710
The air can escape
through the valve

00:09:20.710 --> 00:09:22.900
so it doesn't interfere with
the resin making a good seal.

00:09:22.900 --> 00:09:24.920
Then you close the valve,
and you've sealed the breach.

00:09:24.920 --> 00:09:26.990
The tricky part was getting
the antenna out of the way.

00:09:26.990 --> 00:09:28.290
I pulled it out as
fast as I could,

00:09:28.290 --> 00:09:30.581
wincing as the sudden pressure
drop dizzied me and made

00:09:30.581 --> 00:09:32.649
the wound in my side
scream in agony.

00:09:32.649 --> 00:09:34.690
I got the breach kit over
the hole and sealed it.

00:09:34.690 --> 00:09:35.320
It held.

00:09:35.320 --> 00:09:37.960
The suit back-filled the missing
air with yet more oxygen.

00:09:37.960 --> 00:09:41.100
Checking my arm readouts, I saw
the suit was now at 85% oxygen.

00:09:41.100 --> 00:09:43.690
For reference, Earth's
atmosphere is about 21%.

00:09:43.690 --> 00:09:46.690
I'd be OK so long as I didn't
spend too much time like that.

00:09:46.690 --> 00:09:48.470
I stumbled up the
hill back to the Hab.

00:09:48.470 --> 00:09:49.810
As I crested the
rise, I saw something

00:09:49.810 --> 00:09:51.351
that made me very
happy and something

00:09:51.351 --> 00:09:52.270
that made me very sad.

00:09:52.270 --> 00:09:53.310
The Hab was intact.

00:09:53.310 --> 00:09:53.900
Yay!

00:09:53.900 --> 00:09:55.005
And the MAV was gone.

00:09:55.005 --> 00:09:55.505
Boo!

00:09:58.729 --> 00:10:00.520
Right at that moment,
I knew I was screwed.

00:10:00.520 --> 00:10:02.200
But I didn't want to just
die out on the surface.

00:10:02.200 --> 00:10:04.500
I limped back to the Hab
and fumbled my way out

00:10:04.500 --> 00:10:05.560
into an airlock.

00:10:05.560 --> 00:10:07.552
As soon as it equalized,
I threw off my helmet.

00:10:07.552 --> 00:10:09.135
Once inside the Hab,
I doffed the suit

00:10:09.135 --> 00:10:10.922
and got my first good
look at the injury.

00:10:10.922 --> 00:10:11.880
It would need stitches.

00:10:11.880 --> 00:10:13.504
Fortunately, all of
us had been trained

00:10:13.504 --> 00:10:16.000
in basic medical
procedures and the Hab

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:17.819
had excellent medical supplies.

00:10:17.819 --> 00:10:20.110
A quick shot of a local
anesthetic, irrigate the wound,

00:10:20.110 --> 00:10:21.440
nine stitches, and I was done.

00:10:21.440 --> 00:10:23.440
I'd be taking antibiotics
for a couple of weeks,

00:10:23.440 --> 00:10:24.774
but other than that I'd be fine.

00:10:24.774 --> 00:10:26.523
I knew it was hopeless,
but I tried firing

00:10:26.523 --> 00:10:27.720
up the communications array.

00:10:27.720 --> 00:10:28.704
No signal, of course.

00:10:28.704 --> 00:10:30.870
The primary satellite dish
had broken off, remember?

00:10:30.870 --> 00:10:33.260
And it took the reception
antennae with it.

00:10:33.260 --> 00:10:35.660
The Hab had secondary and
tertiary communication systems,

00:10:35.660 --> 00:10:37.118
but they were both
just for talking

00:10:37.118 --> 00:10:39.630
to the MAV, which would use
it's much more powerful systems

00:10:39.630 --> 00:10:40.505
to relay to "Hermes."

00:10:40.505 --> 00:10:43.420
The thing is, that only works
if the MAV is still around.

00:10:43.420 --> 00:10:44.870
I had no way to
talk to "Hermes."

00:10:44.870 --> 00:10:46.610
In time, I could locate
the dish on the surface,

00:10:46.610 --> 00:10:48.420
but it would take weeks for
me to rig up any repairs

00:10:48.420 --> 00:10:49.544
and that would be too late.

00:10:49.544 --> 00:10:52.134
In an abort, "Hermes" would
leave within 24 hours.

00:10:52.134 --> 00:10:54.300
The orbital dynamics made
the trip safer and shorter

00:10:54.300 --> 00:10:55.260
the earlier you left.

00:10:55.260 --> 00:10:56.566
So why wait?

00:10:56.566 --> 00:10:58.190
Checking out my suit,
I saw the antenna

00:10:58.190 --> 00:10:59.910
had plowed through my
biomonitor computer.

00:10:59.910 --> 00:11:01.421
When on an EVA, all
the crew's suits

00:11:01.421 --> 00:11:03.420
are networked so we can
see each other's status.

00:11:03.420 --> 00:11:05.550
The rest of the crew would have
seen the pressure in my suit

00:11:05.550 --> 00:11:07.216
drop to nearly zero
followed immediately

00:11:07.216 --> 00:11:09.090
by my biosigns going flat.

00:11:09.090 --> 00:11:11.477
Add to that, watching me
tumble down a hill with a spear

00:11:11.477 --> 00:11:13.060
threw me in the
middle of a sandstorm?

00:11:13.060 --> 00:11:14.460
Yeah, they thought I was dead.

00:11:14.460 --> 00:11:16.192
How could they not?

00:11:16.192 --> 00:11:17.900
They may have even
had a brief discussion

00:11:17.900 --> 00:11:20.270
about recovering my body,
but regulations were clear.

00:11:20.270 --> 00:11:22.737
In the event a crewman dies
on Mars, he stays on Mars.

00:11:22.737 --> 00:11:25.320
Leaving his body behind reduces
weight for the MAV on the trip

00:11:25.320 --> 00:11:25.690
back.

00:11:25.690 --> 00:11:27.815
That means more disposable
fuel and a larger margin

00:11:27.815 --> 00:11:29.320
of error for the return thrust.

00:11:29.320 --> 00:11:31.640
No point in giving that
up for sentimentality.

00:11:31.640 --> 00:11:32.930
So that's the situation.

00:11:32.930 --> 00:11:33.840
I'm stranded on Mars.

00:11:33.840 --> 00:11:35.650
I have no way to communicate
with "Hermes" or Earth.

00:11:35.650 --> 00:11:36.840
Everyone thinks I'm dead.

00:11:36.840 --> 00:11:38.860
I'm in a Hab designed
to last 31 days.

00:11:38.860 --> 00:11:40.789
If the oxygenator breaks
down, I'll suffocate.

00:11:40.789 --> 00:11:43.080
If the water reclaimer breaks
down, I'll die of thirst.

00:11:43.080 --> 00:11:45.060
If the Hab breaches, I'll
just kind of explode.

00:11:45.060 --> 00:11:46.560
If none of those
things happen, I'll

00:11:46.560 --> 00:11:48.518
eventually run out of
food and starve to death.

00:11:48.518 --> 00:11:49.743
So yeah, I'm fucked.

00:11:49.743 --> 00:11:50.689
[LAUGHTER]

00:11:50.689 --> 00:11:56.370
[APPLAUSE]

00:11:56.370 --> 00:11:57.780
So that's chapter one.

00:11:59.895 --> 00:12:01.770
Of the things that was
really important to me

00:12:01.770 --> 00:12:03.395
in writing this was
I wanted everything

00:12:03.395 --> 00:12:05.960
to be as scientifically
accurate as possible.

00:12:05.960 --> 00:12:07.510
So for starters,
all the technology

00:12:07.510 --> 00:12:10.690
mentioned in the book is real.

00:12:10.690 --> 00:12:12.360
It takes place in
a slight future,

00:12:12.360 --> 00:12:15.530
so some of the technology is
much more efficient or much

00:12:15.530 --> 00:12:18.200
more effective than the
versions of it we have now.

00:12:18.200 --> 00:12:20.970
But it all actually exists.

00:12:20.970 --> 00:12:22.600
And what I'm going
to talk to you today

00:12:22.600 --> 00:12:24.225
about-- being a Google
crowd, I thought

00:12:24.225 --> 00:12:26.225
you might be interested
in some software I wrote

00:12:26.225 --> 00:12:29.880
to make one part of it
as accurate as possible.

00:12:29.880 --> 00:12:32.890
It has to do with the way that
"Hermes" got from Earth to Mars

00:12:32.890 --> 00:12:34.200
and back.

00:12:34.200 --> 00:12:36.124
"Hermes" is an ion engine ship.

00:12:36.124 --> 00:12:38.540
And for those of you who don't
know what ion engines are--

00:12:38.540 --> 00:12:41.640
I mean, I described it
briefly in the chapter--

00:12:41.640 --> 00:12:43.864
but basically, instead
of a chemical propellant

00:12:43.864 --> 00:12:45.530
going out the back
of the ship providing

00:12:45.530 --> 00:12:48.340
a large amount of impulse,
it's a very small amount

00:12:48.340 --> 00:12:50.450
of acceleration caused
by magnetic fields

00:12:50.450 --> 00:12:52.370
throwing ions out
the back of the ship.

00:12:52.370 --> 00:12:54.600
Now the benefit to
this is that you

00:12:54.600 --> 00:12:57.190
can have much, much,
much less reactant mass.

00:12:57.190 --> 00:12:59.970
And I believe-- and this is
just my own subjective opinion--

00:12:59.970 --> 00:13:03.476
we have to improve on the
technology that we have

00:13:03.476 --> 00:13:04.600
and just keep working that.

00:13:04.600 --> 00:13:05.975
I think that's
the only way we'll

00:13:05.975 --> 00:13:09.920
be able to send humans long
distances out into space.

00:13:09.920 --> 00:13:12.520
The amount of
chemical propellant

00:13:12.520 --> 00:13:14.830
you would need to send
something big enough

00:13:14.830 --> 00:13:17.890
to support humans for
several months out to Mars

00:13:17.890 --> 00:13:19.780
would just be huge, huge.

00:13:19.780 --> 00:13:21.700
I mean, you'd be putting
millions and millions

00:13:21.700 --> 00:13:24.670
of kilograms of just fuel
into space to do this.

00:13:24.670 --> 00:13:27.690
So you need to
minimize how much you

00:13:27.690 --> 00:13:29.930
launch from Earth to
make that efficient.

00:13:29.930 --> 00:13:32.810
So that means for "Hermes,"
I decided, oh, OK,

00:13:32.810 --> 00:13:35.400
so it's got a slow constant
acceleration from ion engines.

00:13:35.400 --> 00:13:36.780
It's got a nuclear
reactor aboard

00:13:36.780 --> 00:13:39.470
to create the energy necessary
to throw the particles.

00:13:39.470 --> 00:13:44.990
And so that means I needed to
figure out how it gets there.

00:13:44.990 --> 00:13:47.500
And it turns out for a point
acceleration, when you just

00:13:47.500 --> 00:13:50.230
say, oh, I want to go on
a transfer orbit from here

00:13:50.230 --> 00:13:51.020
to here.

00:13:51.020 --> 00:13:52.730
And then there'll be
a point thrust here,

00:13:52.730 --> 00:13:54.320
and then another
point thrust here

00:13:54.320 --> 00:13:56.710
to match Mars, boom,
that's how we do it.

00:13:56.710 --> 00:13:57.690
It's very simple.

00:13:57.690 --> 00:13:59.850
Well, I mean, for
a dork like me who

00:13:59.850 --> 00:14:02.260
likes orbital dynamics,
that's very simple.

00:14:02.260 --> 00:14:05.520
With a constantly accelerating
ship, that's very hard.

00:14:05.520 --> 00:14:07.230
I could not wrap my
head around the math.

00:14:07.230 --> 00:14:08.590
I couldn't find
anybody who could

00:14:08.590 --> 00:14:09.964
wrap their heads
around the math.

00:14:09.964 --> 00:14:12.080
And what I found out by
doing further research

00:14:12.080 --> 00:14:14.900
is NASA does this by
computer simulation.

00:14:14.900 --> 00:14:15.900
So that's what I did.

00:14:18.420 --> 00:14:21.452
I wrote this program
called Orbits.

00:14:21.452 --> 00:14:22.910
I don't how well
that's showing up.

00:14:22.910 --> 00:14:23.701
Let me take a look.

00:14:23.701 --> 00:14:24.950
Are you able to see?

00:14:24.950 --> 00:14:26.100
Yeah, you can kind of see.

00:14:26.100 --> 00:14:27.770
It's a little darker
than I'd like.

00:14:27.770 --> 00:14:33.070
But this-- well, I've got
a mouse-- this circle here,

00:14:33.070 --> 00:14:35.180
this red circle, is Mars' orbit.

00:14:35.180 --> 00:14:37.240
The blue circle
is Earth's orbit.

00:14:37.240 --> 00:14:40.270
And the gray line is
the course of the ship.

00:14:40.270 --> 00:14:44.940
So the way this works is I can
mess around with the vector

00:14:44.940 --> 00:14:48.940
that the ship is presenting
with respect to the sun.

00:14:48.940 --> 00:14:51.290
So in other words, if I were
to point it directly away

00:14:51.290 --> 00:14:55.060
from the sun, then I can
show where that vector's

00:14:55.060 --> 00:14:56.747
going to be anywhere
along the trip.

00:14:56.747 --> 00:14:58.830
You see how it's always
pointed away from the sun?

00:14:58.830 --> 00:15:01.640
The red vector that's
following the mouse?

00:15:01.640 --> 00:15:02.980
That's how this works.

00:15:02.980 --> 00:15:05.260
And so I can do
something like this.

00:15:05.260 --> 00:15:07.280
I can point it-- well,
directly toward the sun

00:15:07.280 --> 00:15:08.530
leads to your immediate death.

00:15:08.530 --> 00:15:11.052
But point it, say,
perpendicular to the sun,

00:15:11.052 --> 00:15:12.510
you can see it's
just always trying

00:15:12.510 --> 00:15:14.210
to go perpendicular to the sun.

00:15:14.210 --> 00:15:16.140
So what I wanted
to do here is, say,

00:15:16.140 --> 00:15:17.750
this is the start
point of Earth.

00:15:17.750 --> 00:15:19.794
And as you see, if
I move along, it

00:15:19.794 --> 00:15:21.210
shows me where
Earth and Mars will

00:15:21.210 --> 00:15:24.150
be as they're going
along in their orbits

00:15:24.150 --> 00:15:28.170
from my chosen launch window.

00:15:28.170 --> 00:15:31.180
And then the idea is
to try to find a way

00:15:31.180 --> 00:15:38.940
to make this get to Mars
with course changes and stuff

00:15:38.940 --> 00:15:41.690
and work that out.

00:15:41.690 --> 00:15:45.210
This would not be
a successful trip.

00:15:45.210 --> 00:15:48.230
But after all a whole bunch of
work and just fiddling around

00:15:48.230 --> 00:15:52.930
with it, I managed to figure out
this path that actually starts

00:15:52.930 --> 00:15:56.380
here, then intercepts
Mars, and then

00:15:56.380 --> 00:15:58.630
doesn't do any thrusting
or anything for a while.

00:15:58.630 --> 00:16:00.290
It's just at Mars.

00:16:00.290 --> 00:16:02.460
And then comes back to Earth.

00:16:02.460 --> 00:16:04.980
I also set up this
app to animate.

00:16:04.980 --> 00:16:08.860
So I can just press Space,
and you can watch it happen.

00:16:08.860 --> 00:16:10.770
There it goes to
Mars, hangs out there

00:16:10.770 --> 00:16:13.420
for their planned
31-day mission,

00:16:13.420 --> 00:16:17.040
and then comes back
to Earth like that.

00:16:17.040 --> 00:16:18.900
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] a year.

00:16:18.900 --> 00:16:21.310
ANDY WEIR: It takes a
little bit more than a year.

00:16:21.310 --> 00:16:23.351
I don't know if you can
read it up in the corner.

00:16:23.351 --> 00:16:27.680
Mission day 396 is
when it completes.

00:16:27.680 --> 00:16:30.230
Now, then, as I
mentioned in the book,

00:16:30.230 --> 00:16:35.390
they had to abort after only six
days on Mars due to the storm.

00:16:35.390 --> 00:16:37.510
And I mentioned,
the orbital dynamics

00:16:37.510 --> 00:16:39.680
make it cheaper the
earlier you leave.

00:16:39.680 --> 00:16:40.560
And this is why.

00:16:40.560 --> 00:16:43.440
Because if you
leave earlier, you

00:16:43.440 --> 00:16:45.140
can take a slightly
different course

00:16:45.140 --> 00:16:47.080
and get back to Earth earlier.

00:16:47.080 --> 00:16:49.180
And that's, of course,
what anybody would want.

00:16:49.180 --> 00:16:52.940
Any NASA mission
designer worth their salt

00:16:52.940 --> 00:16:54.920
would want to do
something like this.

00:16:54.920 --> 00:16:58.910
Another thing I did
was-- it came up

00:16:58.910 --> 00:17:01.720
a lot in the story-- I
wanted the transmission

00:17:01.720 --> 00:17:02.820
times to be accurate.

00:17:02.820 --> 00:17:05.970
So when later on in the story
they're talking to the ship,

00:17:05.970 --> 00:17:09.420
they're talking to Mars,
Mars is talking to Earth,

00:17:09.420 --> 00:17:11.010
all these entities
are communicating,

00:17:11.010 --> 00:17:13.839
and I wanted to know what the
transmission time would be.

00:17:13.839 --> 00:17:16.849
So I set it up so that
wherever the ship is--

00:17:16.849 --> 00:17:20.040
I can just move the
mouse around and wherever

00:17:20.040 --> 00:17:23.030
I'm pointing on that-- it'll
tell you what mission day it is

00:17:23.030 --> 00:17:24.869
and what the current
distances are

00:17:24.869 --> 00:17:26.663
between Earth and Mars,
Earth and "Hermes,"

00:17:26.663 --> 00:17:27.579
and "Hermes" and Mars.

00:17:27.579 --> 00:17:30.890
Those are those three numbers up
top, and the light transmission

00:17:30.890 --> 00:17:32.850
time between them
so that I could

00:17:32.850 --> 00:17:36.090
have that be accurate
in the story, too.

00:17:36.090 --> 00:17:38.790
So I'm going to give a
little bit of a spoiler here.

00:17:38.790 --> 00:17:42.640
The final path that "Hermes"
ends up taking is this.

00:17:45.930 --> 00:17:46.750
And so--

00:17:46.750 --> 00:17:48.333
AUDIENCE: It looks
like the other one.

00:17:50.546 --> 00:17:52.420
ANDY WEIR: So I am giving
a bit of a spoiler,

00:17:52.420 --> 00:17:54.920
