to go back to Mars.

00:17:54.920 --> 00:17:59.420
And so I'll describe what
happens as it's happening.

00:17:59.420 --> 00:18:00.120
Here they go.

00:18:00.120 --> 00:18:01.300
They're going to Mars.

00:18:01.300 --> 00:18:03.480
After six Sols,
they have to abort.

00:18:03.480 --> 00:18:06.220
So they're headed back to Earth.

00:18:06.220 --> 00:18:07.490
They need to go back to Mars.

00:18:07.490 --> 00:18:10.910
Boom, sling shot off of
Earth, back around the sun.

00:18:10.910 --> 00:18:13.124
And now they need to
do a flyby of Mars.

00:18:13.124 --> 00:18:14.790
So they're not going
into orbit, they're

00:18:14.790 --> 00:18:16.710
just-- doink-- doing a flyby.

00:18:16.710 --> 00:18:19.065
And then we got to
get back to Earth.

00:18:24.290 --> 00:18:29.450
So that was a lot of
work to figure that out.

00:18:29.450 --> 00:18:31.620
And this is all done
within this simulation,

00:18:31.620 --> 00:18:34.790
this ship "Hermes," has a
total constant acceleration

00:18:34.790 --> 00:18:37.340
of the two millimeters
per second per second.

00:18:37.340 --> 00:18:38.010
That's it.

00:18:38.010 --> 00:18:39.680
That's all it gets.

00:18:39.680 --> 00:18:42.850
So yeah, after five
seconds of doing that,

00:18:42.850 --> 00:18:46.960
it would be moving one
centimeter per second.

00:18:46.960 --> 00:18:50.560
So that's the software I wrote
that I wanted to show off.

00:18:50.560 --> 00:18:56.611
I thought the Google crowd would
like to see how that works.

00:18:56.611 --> 00:18:57.860
And that's about it, actually.

00:18:57.860 --> 00:19:00.080
That's all I really
had to show you.

