00:19:41.560 --> 00:19:43.250
Log entry, Sol 27.

00:19:43.250 --> 00:19:44.760
Log entry, Sol 412.

00:19:44.760 --> 00:19:45.770
Whatever.

00:19:45.770 --> 00:19:48.360
So it's actually very
time specific, just

00:19:48.360 --> 00:19:50.210
the narrative style it has.

00:19:50.210 --> 00:19:53.590
And so I made sure that I knew
the actual real-world date

00:19:53.590 --> 00:19:56.600
for each-- on any given
day in the book, what

00:19:56.600 --> 00:19:59.790
the real-world date is so that
I could mention things like, oh,

00:19:59.790 --> 00:20:01.040
by the way, today's Christmas.

00:20:01.040 --> 00:20:02.940
And it is.

00:20:02.940 --> 00:20:05.250
There were sometimes
I had to keep myself

00:20:05.250 --> 00:20:07.040
from over clever-ing things.

00:20:07.040 --> 00:20:09.440
There was one kind of major
plot point that happened.

00:20:09.440 --> 00:20:11.370
And I'm looking
at my spreadsheet.

00:20:11.370 --> 00:20:13.920
And I'm like, oh, this happens
to be on Valentine's Day.

00:20:13.920 --> 00:20:14.960
I should mention that.

00:20:14.960 --> 00:20:16.930
But it would just seem
stupid to the reader.

00:20:16.930 --> 00:20:18.590
It would be like out of nowhere
someone's like, by the way,

00:20:18.590 --> 00:20:20.020
it's Valentine's Day.

00:20:20.020 --> 00:20:22.950
It's like, no, that's just dumb.

00:20:22.950 --> 00:20:25.840
The trickiest part in this
was I did all sorts of math.

00:20:25.840 --> 00:20:28.570
I checked all my physics,
math, science, everything.

00:20:28.570 --> 00:20:32.257
And the hard part was not
bragging to the reader.

00:20:32.257 --> 00:20:34.590
It was not showing my work
and trying to go, look at me.

00:20:34.590 --> 00:20:35.445
I'm so cool.

00:20:35.445 --> 00:20:37.320
I just needed to keep
the story moving along.

00:20:37.320 --> 00:20:38.611
And I wanted it to be accurate.

00:20:38.611 --> 00:20:39.120
That's all.

00:20:39.120 --> 00:20:41.870
AUDIENCE: So I read the
book about a year ago.

00:20:41.870 --> 00:20:43.789
What I enjoyed the
most about it were

00:20:43.789 --> 00:20:45.080
two things about the character.

00:20:45.080 --> 00:20:47.230
One was how resourceful he is.

00:20:47.230 --> 00:20:50.790
He always figures out how
to get out of his situation.

00:20:50.790 --> 00:20:52.620
The other was his attitude.

00:20:52.620 --> 00:20:53.700
He's cut off.

00:20:53.700 --> 00:20:54.700
He has so many setbacks.

00:20:54.700 --> 00:20:56.033
And he always keeps his head up.

00:20:56.033 --> 00:20:57.600
I was wondering,
was there anything

00:20:57.600 --> 00:20:59.750
that inspired you to make
a character like that?

00:20:59.750 --> 00:21:01.374
Or was there any kind
of message you're

00:21:01.374 --> 00:21:03.710
trying to send to make
somebody so resourceful and so

00:21:03.710 --> 00:21:06.710
optimistic in such
a bad situation?

00:21:06.710 --> 00:21:09.440
ANDY WEIR: Well, I
mean, I tried to make

00:21:09.440 --> 00:21:10.610
it a pretty upbeat book.

00:21:10.610 --> 00:21:12.806
It could've been really
dark and depressing, right?

00:21:12.806 --> 00:21:14.180
It's like the guys
trapped alone.

00:21:14.180 --> 00:21:16.840
He could be just having
this crippling psychological

00:21:16.840 --> 00:21:19.560
problems of loneliness
and all these other things

00:21:19.560 --> 00:21:20.930
that most people would face.

00:21:20.930 --> 00:21:23.050
I figure I can buy
my way out of that

00:21:23.050 --> 00:21:24.510
by saying he's an astronaut.

00:21:24.510 --> 00:21:26.190
Astronauts are a cut above.

00:21:26.190 --> 00:21:28.350
And so he doesn't
sink into depression.

00:21:28.350 --> 00:21:30.320
He just goes into
problem-solving mode.

00:21:30.320 --> 00:21:33.790
And I made him this really
flippant, smart-ass personality

00:21:33.790 --> 00:21:36.140
because I had to
tell a whole story.

00:21:36.140 --> 00:21:40.430
If I'd done just
blank narration, just

00:21:40.430 --> 00:21:43.550
omniscient narration even,
it would have just seemed

00:21:43.550 --> 00:21:47.190
like a technical manual or a
really dry sequence of events.

00:21:47.190 --> 00:21:49.550
I needed something in
the narration itself

00:21:49.550 --> 00:21:51.600
that would keep the
user interested.

00:21:51.600 --> 00:21:54.655
And so having it told by a
self-effacing smart-ass seemed

00:21:54.655 --> 00:21:55.679
liked a good idea.

00:21:55.679 --> 00:21:57.720
AUDIENCE: So I'm thinking
about buying this book.

00:21:57.720 --> 00:21:59.110
ANDY WEIR: $10 right over there.

00:21:59.110 --> 00:22:00.290
AUDIENCE: How do you
think I should buy it?

00:22:00.290 --> 00:22:00.956
ANDY WEIR: I think you should
buy one for all your friends.

00:22:00.956 --> 00:22:02.530
AUDIENCE: It's $10
right over there,

00:22:02.530 --> 00:22:05.090
but there's also a lot
of digital distribution

00:22:05.090 --> 00:22:06.070
around these days.

00:22:06.070 --> 00:22:09.010
Do you have thoughts as
an author about that?

00:22:09.010 --> 00:22:10.420
And what works best for you?

00:22:10.420 --> 00:22:12.250
What do you like as a reader?

00:22:12.250 --> 00:22:15.307
And what do you think about
ebooks in general as an author?

00:22:15.307 --> 00:22:17.640
ANDY WEIR: Well, ebooks are
how I got into the industry,

00:22:17.640 --> 00:22:19.590
so I'm extremely grateful.

00:22:19.590 --> 00:22:21.800
I think they're great.

00:22:21.800 --> 00:22:24.900
And as for buying a
physical book or an ebook,

00:22:24.900 --> 00:22:26.780
that's a matter of
personal choice.

00:22:26.780 --> 00:22:28.930
I still read physical
books, but that's

00:22:28.930 --> 00:22:30.620
just because I'm
kind of a Luddite.

00:22:30.620 --> 00:22:33.470
Eventually, I will
get a proper e-reader.

00:22:33.470 --> 00:22:36.080
And then I'll probably be
hooked on that from then on.

00:22:38.654 --> 00:22:40.570
For those of you who
don't know, "The Martian"

00:22:40.570 --> 00:22:42.240
was originally
just a serial story

00:22:42.240 --> 00:22:44.080
that I was posting
to my website just

00:22:44.080 --> 00:22:46.830
as a hobby doing
in my spare time.

00:22:46.830 --> 00:22:49.430
And then I finished
and some people

00:22:49.430 --> 00:22:51.970
said, hey, I don't like
reading this on web pages.

00:22:51.970 --> 00:22:54.387
Can you put it up
in an ebook format?

00:22:54.387 --> 00:22:55.220
And so I'm like, OK.

00:22:55.220 --> 00:22:56.759
So I made an EPUB
and MOBI version.

00:22:56.759 --> 00:22:58.800
And I posted them on the
website and said, there.

00:22:58.800 --> 00:22:59.000
There you go.

00:22:59.000 --> 00:23:00.640
Free download,
knock yourself out.

00:23:00.640 --> 00:23:02.880
And then some people
were like, well,

00:23:02.880 --> 00:23:04.480
I'm not really
technically savvy.

00:23:04.480 --> 00:23:07.300
And I don't know how to
get an ebook downloaded

00:23:07.300 --> 00:23:09.280
from the internet
onto my Kindle.

00:23:09.280 --> 00:23:12.380
Is there a way you can
just put it up on Kindle?

00:23:12.380 --> 00:23:13.760
And so I looked into it.

00:23:13.760 --> 00:23:16.824
And anybody can post
their stuff onto Kindle.

00:23:16.824 --> 00:23:18.990
Which is important-- remember
that-- because anybody

00:23:18.990 --> 00:23:20.720
who wants to be a
writer, you just can.

00:23:20.720 --> 00:23:24.036
You can just write your
story, post it on Kindle.

00:23:24.036 --> 00:23:25.410
All they do is
they check to make

00:23:25.410 --> 00:23:28.870
sure there's nothing illegal or
really, really evil about what

00:23:28.870 --> 00:23:30.180
you're posting.

00:23:30.180 --> 00:23:34.100
And so I posted it up on Kindle.

00:23:34.100 --> 00:23:36.720
But Amazon is not a charity.

00:23:36.720 --> 00:23:37.970
They're in this to make money.

00:23:37.970 --> 00:23:39.520
They have a minimum
price that you're

00:23:39.520 --> 00:23:41.780
allowed to charge,
which is $0.99,

00:23:41.780 --> 00:23:43.490
or at least it was at the time.

00:23:43.490 --> 00:23:46.080
And so I said, OK, I'll
set the price at $0.99.

00:23:46.080 --> 00:23:47.867
I'm not allowed to charge less.

00:23:47.867 --> 00:23:49.450
And I told everybody,
hey, here it is.

00:23:49.450 --> 00:23:51.590
It's $0.99 because I can't
charge less than that.

00:23:51.590 --> 00:23:52.470
Just look at it this way.

00:23:52.470 --> 00:23:54.344
If you want to pay $1
to have it conveniently

00:23:54.344 --> 00:23:57.720
delivered to your Kindle,
that's what you're paying for.

00:23:57.720 --> 00:24:01.690
I got $0.30 or something
out of that per copy.

00:24:01.690 --> 00:24:03.940
I mean, I was not doing
this for the money.

00:24:03.940 --> 00:24:07.100
And then that's when
I learned how deep

00:24:07.100 --> 00:24:11.550
Amazon's reach into the
readership market is.

00:24:11.550 --> 00:24:15.440
Many, many, many more people--
many multiples more people--

00:24:15.440 --> 00:24:18.560
bought it from Amazon than
downloaded it for free

00:24:18.560 --> 00:24:19.120
from my site.

00:24:21.954 --> 00:24:22.870
AUDIENCE: Such a deal.

00:24:22.870 --> 00:24:23.828
ANDY WEIR: Such a deal.

00:24:23.828 --> 00:24:25.690
I'm like, OK.

00:24:25.690 --> 00:24:28.420
And that caused
it to start making

00:24:28.420 --> 00:24:30.960
its way up the top
sellers charts.

00:24:30.960 --> 00:24:33.120
And then once it got into
the top 10 on sci-fi,

00:24:33.120 --> 00:24:34.411
then it started to really sell.

00:24:34.411 --> 00:24:36.840
Because of course, people
are like, I want a sci-fi.

00:24:36.840 --> 00:24:38.080
What's in the top 10?

00:24:38.080 --> 00:24:40.610
So once you break
into that list,

00:24:40.610 --> 00:24:43.312
your sales go really well.

00:24:43.312 --> 00:24:44.770
And it sold well
enough that it got

00:24:44.770 --> 00:24:48.600
the attention of a guy
named Julian Pavia at Random

00:24:48.600 --> 00:24:50.310
House, who was an editor there.

00:24:50.310 --> 00:24:51.919
And he said, I like this book.

00:24:51.919 --> 00:24:54.460
I think I want to talk to this
reader and offer a print deal.

00:24:54.460 --> 00:24:56.668
But first I'm going to run
it by a colleague of mine,

00:24:56.668 --> 00:24:58.919
a guy named David Fugate,
who is a literary agent.

00:24:58.919 --> 00:25:00.710
He said, hey, why don't
you read this book,

00:25:00.710 --> 00:25:01.920
tell me what you
think, and do you

00:25:01.920 --> 00:25:03.711
think I should offer
this guy a print deal?

00:25:03.711 --> 00:25:06.480
David read it and said,
I think it's good.

00:25:06.480 --> 00:25:08.230
I think you should
offer him a print deal.

00:25:08.230 --> 00:25:09.010
Now hang on a second.

00:25:09.010 --> 00:25:10.385
I'm going to go
become his agent.

00:25:13.180 --> 00:25:14.002
So he did.

00:25:14.002 --> 00:25:15.460
And then he turned
around and said,

00:25:15.460 --> 00:25:18.350
so Julian, let's talk money.

00:25:18.350 --> 00:25:20.030
So that was pretty cool.

00:25:20.030 --> 00:25:23.390
So my whole experience
with publishing

00:25:23.390 --> 00:25:26.430
has been completely backwards.

00:25:26.430 --> 00:25:30.360
I wrote what I intended
to be just a free thing

00:25:30.360 --> 00:25:32.020
and then got forced
to charge for it.

00:25:32.020 --> 00:25:33.870
And then an agent came
knocking at my door.

00:25:33.870 --> 00:25:36.510
And then a publisher came
offering me a contract.

00:25:36.510 --> 00:25:38.850
And I did nothing to
promote it ever, by the way.

00:25:38.850 --> 00:25:40.700
All I ever did was just post it.

00:25:40.700 --> 00:25:43.350
I didn't even try
to go to forums

00:25:43.350 --> 00:25:45.780
or do events or anything
to get people to read it.

00:25:45.780 --> 00:25:47.820
It just spread by word of mouth.

00:25:47.820 --> 00:25:52.110
So the long-ass winded
answer to your question

00:25:52.110 --> 00:25:58.690
is I'm a big fan of digital
books because that made me.

00:25:58.690 --> 00:26:01.780
Sorry, one last addendum--
and it can make anyone.

00:26:01.780 --> 00:26:03.480
That's what I think
is awesome, is

00:26:03.480 --> 00:26:05.045
it's become a pure meritocracy.

00:26:05.045 --> 00:26:07.460
It used to be sort of
an old-boy network.

00:26:07.460 --> 00:26:10.700
You had to know somebody to get
into the publishing industry

00:26:10.700 --> 00:26:11.200
at all.

00:26:11.200 --> 00:26:14.770
Or you had to dedicate your
life to doing scutt work

00:26:14.770 --> 00:26:16.520
and working your way
up through journalism

00:26:16.520 --> 00:26:18.395
until someone would take
you seriously enough

00:26:18.395 --> 00:26:21.430
even to consider reading your
book at a publishing house.

00:26:21.430 --> 00:26:23.890
But now you can post it yourself
with no intervening steps

00:26:23.890 --> 00:26:26.970
and, if it's good,
people will buy it.

00:26:26.970 --> 00:26:32.330
AUDIENCE: So your ion drive,
is the reaction mass just small

00:26:32.330 --> 00:26:35.890
enough so that you don't
account for the change

00:26:35.890 --> 00:26:37.680
in how much acceleration
it can give?

00:26:37.680 --> 00:26:38.940
ANDY WEIR: I cheated.

00:26:38.940 --> 00:26:41.265
The answer is it
wouldn't quite be.

00:26:41.265 --> 00:26:42.140
It wouldn't quite be.

00:26:42.140 --> 00:26:44.056
And the simulation could
have accounted for it

00:26:44.056 --> 00:26:46.190
since it's doing
incremental-- every step,

00:26:46.190 --> 00:26:48.850
I think I had it do it
in one-hour segments

00:26:48.850 --> 00:26:50.900
to run the simulation forward.

00:26:50.900 --> 00:26:52.900
And so I could have
accounted for the mass loss.

00:26:52.900 --> 00:26:54.120
It is very small.

00:26:54.120 --> 00:26:57.620
It's on the order of-- I
can't remember exactly-- it

00:26:57.620 --> 00:27:00.510
was on the order of 10% of
the ship's mass, though.

00:27:00.510 --> 00:27:03.190
Normally if you
were going to do--

00:27:03.190 --> 00:27:05.885
to get to Mars using
a Hohmann transfer,

00:27:05.885 --> 00:27:09.240
it would take five
kilometers per second delta

00:27:09.240 --> 00:27:12.520
V, which would be
for a ship like this

00:27:12.520 --> 00:27:15.270
that I later defined as
being 110,000 kilograms,

00:27:15.270 --> 00:27:17.610
would be millions and
millions of kilograms of fuel.

00:27:17.610 --> 00:27:21.010
I mean, the vast majority of
the starting mass would be fuel.

00:27:21.010 --> 00:27:24.180
And so once I checked
the specific impulse

00:27:24.180 --> 00:27:26.020
of ion engines,
it's so much better

00:27:26.020 --> 00:27:29.580
than I just said, eh,
I'll approximate it out.

