00:32:28.640 --> 00:32:31.440
ANDY WEIR: I did not
read any of those.

00:32:31.440 --> 00:32:34.290
As for the research, that was
just really important to me.

00:32:34.290 --> 00:32:37.590
I just wanted to be as
accurate as I possibly could.

00:32:37.590 --> 00:32:39.422
There are a few places
that are inaccurate.

00:32:39.422 --> 00:32:40.880
The biggest place
that's inaccurate

00:32:40.880 --> 00:32:43.260
is right at the beginning.

00:32:43.260 --> 00:32:46.350
Don't tell anybody, but if
you're in a dust storm on Mars,

00:32:46.350 --> 00:32:47.820
you're not even
going to feel it.

00:32:47.820 --> 00:32:50.290
Mars' atmosphere is
less than 1% of Earth's.

00:32:50.290 --> 00:32:53.360
So a 150 kilometer an
hour wind would feel

00:32:53.360 --> 00:32:56.190
like about a 1 kilometer
an hour wind does on Earth.

00:32:56.190 --> 00:32:57.780
It wouldn't do any
damage to anything.

00:32:57.780 --> 00:32:59.760
Shh.

00:32:59.760 --> 00:33:01.090
I had other ways of doing it.

00:33:01.090 --> 00:33:04.930
I had an idea where the MAV
would have some sort of failure

00:33:04.930 --> 00:33:07.440
that caused an explosion
which does all the damage.

00:33:07.440 --> 00:33:09.730
And they're short on
time because the MAV fuel

00:33:09.730 --> 00:33:11.480
tank is leaking, so
they need to lift off.

00:33:11.480 --> 00:33:13.521
And they're sure Mark's
dead and stuff like that.

00:33:13.521 --> 00:33:17.945
But most people don't know
how Martian dust storms work.

00:33:17.945 --> 00:33:19.570
Most people don't
realize that it's not

00:33:19.570 --> 00:33:20.910
like being in a sand blaster.

00:33:20.910 --> 00:33:22.451
And it's just more
dramatic that way.

00:33:22.451 --> 00:33:24.220
So I just made that concession.

00:33:24.220 --> 00:33:27.360
I know I'm a liar.

00:33:27.360 --> 00:33:28.870
I just wanted that more.

00:33:28.870 --> 00:33:30.580
It was more dramatic.

