point, try to arrange a mission

00:40:26.340 --> 00:40:28.607
where they would repair
the Hubble from ISS.

00:40:28.607 --> 00:40:30.690
And they could not find
any way to make that work.

00:40:33.550 --> 00:40:36.280
So there are few
errors in "Gravity,"

00:40:36.280 --> 00:40:37.790
but I liked it a lot.

00:40:37.790 --> 00:40:40.740
It is kind of inconvenient,
though, because I released

00:40:40.740 --> 00:40:42.620
"The Martian" before
"Gravity" came out.

00:40:42.620 --> 00:40:44.581
I wrote it all before
"Gravity" came out.

00:40:44.581 --> 00:40:46.080
Now the re-release
of "The Martian,"

00:40:46.080 --> 00:40:49.172
people are like, oh, hey,
this is like "Gravity."

00:40:49.172 --> 00:40:51.000
I'm like, no,
"Gravity"'s like me.

00:40:55.150 --> 00:40:57.209
AUDIENCE: I was
wondering, did you

00:40:57.209 --> 00:40:58.750
manage to get any
input on the cover?

00:40:58.750 --> 00:41:00.520
I mean, it looks really nice.

00:41:00.520 --> 00:41:01.810
ANDY WEIR: Thanks.

00:41:01.810 --> 00:41:03.990
That's actually funny.

00:41:03.990 --> 00:41:06.260
I didn't like it.

00:41:06.260 --> 00:41:10.230
And they said, hey, here's
the cover we're going to go.

00:41:10.230 --> 00:41:11.605
The Random House's
art department

00:41:11.605 --> 00:41:14.400
said-- here's this
whole big thing

00:41:14.400 --> 00:41:17.030
that they did-- and
they said, here it is.

00:41:17.030 --> 00:41:19.650
And I said, I don't like it.

00:41:19.650 --> 00:41:21.330
But everybody else does.

00:41:21.330 --> 00:41:23.450
So I'm glad I was wrong.

00:41:23.450 --> 00:41:24.790
Or I'm glad-- how do I put it?

00:41:24.790 --> 00:41:26.130
I'm glad I didn't have any say.

00:41:30.710 --> 00:41:32.290
Although I did point
out one problem.

00:41:32.290 --> 00:41:36.350
Originally, in the-- that's an
actual photo of an astronaut

00:41:36.350 --> 00:41:39.430
who is on a space shuttle
mission at the time

00:41:39.430 --> 00:41:40.550
this photo was taken.

00:41:40.550 --> 00:41:43.370
I mean, obviously all the
red stuff is Photoshopped.

00:41:43.370 --> 00:41:46.010
But in his helmet, you
could see the reflection

00:41:46.010 --> 00:41:48.180
of the space shuttle cargo bay.

00:41:48.180 --> 00:41:49.390
And I pointed that.

00:41:49.390 --> 00:41:50.360
I'm like, nah.

00:41:50.360 --> 00:41:53.790
So they fixed that.

00:41:53.790 --> 00:41:55.590
AUDIENCE: What would you prefer?

00:41:55.590 --> 00:42:00.720
ANDY WEIR: I imagined--
well, the Dutch cover--

00:42:00.720 --> 00:42:03.140
so every language
that's selling-- it's

00:42:03.140 --> 00:42:05.390
getting translated
into 21 languages

00:42:05.390 --> 00:42:09.160
and pretty much every one of
them has their own cover art.

00:42:09.160 --> 00:42:11.900
And the Dutch cover is
kind of what I liked.

00:42:11.900 --> 00:42:15.800
It's just basically a
lone figure, very small,

00:42:15.800 --> 00:42:19.910
like, in the middle there and
just big, empty Martian scenery

00:42:19.910 --> 00:42:22.070
just to show there's
isolation and stuff.

00:42:22.070 --> 00:42:23.540
And I thought that was cool.

00:42:23.540 --> 00:42:25.460
But this is like--
there are actually

00:42:25.460 --> 00:42:27.662
websites that just judge
books by their cover.

00:42:27.662 --> 00:42:29.120
Like that's literally
what they do.

00:42:29.120 --> 00:42:29.619
They say--

00:42:29.619 --> 00:42:32.594
[LAUGHTER]

00:42:32.594 --> 00:42:34.010
Literally all they
do is they say,

00:42:34.010 --> 00:42:36.160
like, we're rating
covers of new release,

00:42:36.160 --> 00:42:38.820
not the content of
the book, nothing.

00:42:38.820 --> 00:42:41.690
Just think of them as
artistic analysis websites.

00:42:41.690 --> 00:42:44.200
And they loved the
cover of "The Martian."

00:42:44.200 --> 00:42:45.950
AUDIENCE: By the way,
great title, too.

00:42:45.950 --> 00:42:47.379
ANDY WEIR: Thanks.

00:42:47.379 --> 00:42:49.420
Yeah, a lot of people will
say, oh, like pro tip,

00:42:49.420 --> 00:42:52.140
there's no actual
Martians in this.

00:42:52.140 --> 00:42:53.280
There's no aliens.

00:42:53.280 --> 00:42:57.230
He's the Martian, you see,
because he's stuck there.

00:42:57.230 --> 00:42:59.960
MALE SPEAKER: Tell me,
so how did you actually

00:42:59.960 --> 00:43:04.144
start to think about writing
a story of somebody on Mars?

00:43:04.144 --> 00:43:05.810
I know we talked a
little bit about this

00:43:05.810 --> 00:43:07.680
before the talk itself.

00:43:07.680 --> 00:43:10.400
We're sort of an Apollo
generation type of thing.

00:43:10.400 --> 00:43:14.210
But what was that
moment that's, hey,

00:43:14.210 --> 00:43:15.820
I'm going to write
a story about Mars.

00:43:15.820 --> 00:43:16.720
Why?

00:43:16.720 --> 00:43:19.190
ANDY WEIR: Well,
dork that I am, I

00:43:19.190 --> 00:43:22.700
was imagining how a manned
Mars mission could work.

00:43:22.700 --> 00:43:25.700
And so I was just trying
to say, realistically,

00:43:25.700 --> 00:43:27.810
how do you get the
astronauts to Mars?

00:43:27.810 --> 00:43:30.160
How do you build a ship
big enough to support them?

00:43:30.160 --> 00:43:31.251
How does that work?

00:43:31.251 --> 00:43:32.250
How do you get it there?

00:43:32.250 --> 00:43:34.416
That's why I had use ion
engines because it was just

00:43:34.416 --> 00:43:35.754
too implausible otherwise.

00:43:35.754 --> 00:43:37.670
It's like once they're
there, what do they do?

00:43:37.670 --> 00:43:39.380
How do they get back?

00:43:39.380 --> 00:43:41.780
And, oh, you could send all
the supplies in advance.

00:43:41.780 --> 00:43:45.244
It uses heavily from
Mars Direct, which is--

00:43:45.244 --> 00:43:46.410
MALE SPEAKER: Zubrin's plan.

00:43:46.410 --> 00:43:49.460
ANDY WEIR: Yeah,
Zubrin's suggested

00:43:49.460 --> 00:43:52.360
way of doing a Mars
mission, which if and when

00:43:52.360 --> 00:43:54.094
we have a Mars mission
in the real world,

00:43:54.094 --> 00:43:56.510
it will almost certainly be
something very much like that.

00:43:56.510 --> 00:43:59.910
Anyway I was considering all
the things that could go wrong.

00:43:59.910 --> 00:44:01.560
I was saying, any
mission plan has

00:44:01.560 --> 00:44:03.726
to account for things that
can go wrong and say, oh,

00:44:03.726 --> 00:44:05.860
if this happens, then the
astronaut should do this.

00:44:05.860 --> 00:44:07.420
If this happens,
they should do this.

00:44:07.420 --> 00:44:09.670
And I started thinking of
all these failure scenarios.

00:44:09.670 --> 00:44:12.590
And those started to seem
really interesting to me.

00:44:12.590 --> 00:44:14.755
So I made a poor,
hapless main character

00:44:14.755 --> 00:44:15.880
to suffer through them all.

00:44:18.647 --> 00:44:21.230
MALE SPEAKER: The readers won't
suffer if they read this book.

00:44:21.230 --> 00:44:22.140
I'm sure about that.

00:44:22.140 --> 00:44:24.630
So please give
thanks to Andy Weir.

00:44:24.630 --> 00:44:30.828
[APPLAUSE]

